article.description: Marie Ferdinand scored 12 of her 17 points in the second half, and Margo Dydek added 15 points to lead the San Antonio Silver Stars to a 56-44 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Minnesota held to record-low 44
article.linkText: Dydek throws block party vs. weak Lynx
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Margo Dydek doesn't have to start to be
effective for the San Antonio Silver Stars.

The 7-foot-2 center had 15 points and nine blocks in a reserve
role Wednesday night, leading the San Antonio Silver Stars to a
56-44 win over the Minnesota Lynx.

"It's not like I would do anything different if I were to
start," said Dydek, who was replaced in the starting lineup by
Jessie Hicks to give the Silver Stars more speed. "I will always
try to play my best."

Even when she wasn't swatting the ball away, Dydek's presence on
defense frequently altered Minnesota's inside shots.

"Tonight was a lesson learned for Nicole Ohlde," Lynx coach
Suzie McConnell Serio said, referring to her 6-foot-5 rookie
center. "We have players on this team who have faced Dydek before
and know that you can't really hope to shoot over her."

Ohlde, who led Minnesota with 14 points and nine rebounds, was
blocked six times by Dydek.

"This is what she's capable of doing every night," San
Antonio's Marie Ferdinand said of Dydek. "She had a block party
tonight. Everybody was invited."

Ferdinand scored 17 points, 12 in the second half, to lead the
Silver Stars. Adrienne Goodson had nine rebounds.

The Lynx shot only 25 percent in the first half and finished at
32 percent (18-for-56). They missed all 15 of their 3-point
attempts. San Antonio shot 43 percent (22-for-51).

"We played horrible," Minnesota's Teresa Edwards said. "We
gave them the game."

The Lynx, who trailed by 10 at the break, cut San Antonio's lead
to 34-30 on a layup by Ohlde with 14 minutes left.

The Silver Stars then went on a 13-4 run, capped by a layup by
Dydek, and matched their largest lead of the game at 47-34.

Minnesota's 44 points was a franchise low, and a record low
total for a San Antonio opponent.

Katie Smith scored the first basket to give the Lynx their only
lead of the game. Minnesota then missed 16 of their next 19 shots,
but still trailed by just six points midway through the first half.

A layup and a turnaround jumper by Dydek started an 11-2 run
that gave the Silver Stars a 23-10 lead with less than five minutes
left in the half.
